recordings.loc: Orianne Society Mopani Preserve, Telfair Co., Georgia
recordings.rmk: This observation is interesting for a couple reasons. First off, I found the micro-habitat of this ACFL to be a bit odd: near the crest of a fairly xeric sandhill dominated by stunted, scrubby oaks and malnourished, sparse loblolly pines. There are wet sloughs and bottoms within 800 meters of its locality, and which held several ACFLs as expected. However, this bird was relating to a very tight area up on the dry part of the sandhill. Another bird occupied a different apparent territory in the same micro-habitat about 500 meters away from this one. Another interesting tidbit is that the Ruby-throated Hummingbird does not vocalize, but rather the hum of its wings can be heard; this female continued to buzz me several times after the recording, VERY close,  and I worried that I was near her nest. However, it suddenly occurred to me as I watched her movements and considered my own movements (constantly swatting at swarming mosquitoes) that she was actually catching the mosquitoes that were surrounding my body -- as if I was the bait and she was reaping the catch! :)

Alcala, Valle del Cauca
recordings.rmk:
The recording has not been modified at all. The bird was located in a strip of riparian vegetation dominated by Guadua angustifolia (native bamboo species) on the edge of a cattle farm (with moderate tree cover and other crops e.g., citrus, shade-coffee). The bird generally moved between 2 and 5 m from the ground, though the terrain is quite steeply sloped. It behaved as a fairly typical Empidonax flycatcher - sitting still for long periods of time, pumping its tail regularly, flycatching and returning to the same spot, or to a new spot. It changed perches frequently (every ~30 seconds). Weather was overcast, little to no wind.

Field Marks: weak crest, very faint whitish eyering (with very faint trace of a teardrop effect), orange lower mandible with dusky tip, bill length approximately equal to the distance between start of bill and back of eye, drab olive back and nape, two yellowish wingbars (upper bar appeared brownish at times), yellow margins on secondaries, moderate to long primary projection (I'm bad at judging that fieldmark), grayish-white throat, drab olive (dusky) breast, pale yellow belly and vent, medium length tail (shorter than folded wing length).

Field marks taken from photos, can send if desired.

recordings.rmk: Amplified, and then noise reduced.  Bird slightly above head height in saplings within a tall forest remnant near a city park.  Was silent upon discovery.  Played Yellow-bellied Flycatcher song and bird started incessantly calling this call.  I managed to get an iPhone recording of one of the calls and uploaded it to compare sonograms.  Yellow on throat and yellow eyering made me suspect Yellow-bellied but ID is typically defaulted to Acadian in this area, unless the bird vocalizes.

recordings.loc: Marietta, Cobb County, Georgia
recordings.rmk:
This individual was giving particularly loud "whit" vocalizations for a fall migrant. A fair/documentary recording; captured using a simple voice note recorder on an iPhone 4. NOTES: Heard a strong, emphatic, and familiar 'whit! ...whit!' call repetitively from other end of parking lot. A slightly similar call given by LEFL is not as sharp, seems often accommodated by a bubbly note, and I would never expect it to carry so far. The equivalent call of YBFL is very different, longer, higher-pitched: 'ptseee... ptseee' ALFL gives its distinctive 'pip! ...pip!' call. WIFL can have a somewhat similar 'whit' so I began recording the sound as I quickly went to find it. I gladly enjoyed very close looks of this Empidonax flycatcher, undoubtedly an Acadian: soft velvet, gray-green upperparts (green not as rich as YBFL); full round off-white eyering; bill yellow-orange below and dark above; throat patch white in the very center, surrounded by light ashy-gray, then abruptly framed by a defined vertical boarder with the gray-green of the side of the neck. The bird had a pretty but light yellow wash that was restricted to the lower flanks. Wings were black, with two bold off-white wingbars.
